Flattening some arrays is a trivial task with plain JS. Using [`Array.flat`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/flat), you can do this in one line. 

&gt;The flat() method creates a new array with all sub-array elements concatenated into it recursively up to the specified depth.

&gt;**Syntax**

&gt;var newArray = arr.flat([depth]);

&gt;**Parameters**

&gt;depth Optional

&gt;The depth level specifying how deep a nested array structure should be flattened. Defaults to 1.

&gt;**Return value**

&gt;A new array with the sub-array elements concatenated into it.




&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    //one level deep
    var x = [[&#39;A&#39;], [&#39;B&#39;]];
    console.log(x.flat());
    // =&gt; [&#39;A&#39;, &#39;B&#39;]

    //2 levels deep
    var y = [[[&#39;A&#39;, &#39;B&#39;], [&#39;C&#39;]], [&#39;D&#39;]];
    console.log(y.flat(2));
    // =&gt; [&#39;A&#39;, &#39;B&#39;, &#39;C&#39;, &#39;D&#39;]

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

